Quick Notes on Using the Chunk Allocator
========================================

Jonathan Eckstein, November 2000

This note describes the chunkAllocator class.  The idea is that for
small classes that may have many instances, to

(1)  Reduce the number of calls to malloc

(2)  Reduce system memory overhead -- for example, on Janus, each call
     to new/malloc imposes an overhead of 32 bytes.

The idea is that classes using the chunk allocator will allocate large
blocks of memory at a time, reducing the number of system calls and
amortizing any per-allocated-fragment overhead.

If this tool proves satisfactory, we may want to move it from pico to
utilib shorty.

To use chunk allocation for a class, you just have to do three things:

(1) Make sure you #include "memUtil.H" in your class header.

(2) Somewhere within the declaration of the class, insert the line

    #include "chunkAlloc.H"

(this could also be done with a macro, but this method is less
confusing to source-level debuggers).  

(3)  Somewhere in the .C or .cpp code file for the class, insert the
     line

     CHUNK_ALLOCATOR_DEF(<class-name>,<mult>);

where <class-name> is the name of your class, and <mult> is the number
of instances you want to created in each actual call to malloc.  For
classes on the order of 50 bytes, I've been using values of <mult> of
around 100.  

These steps do a number of things

(a) Creates a static memory allocator object for the class.

(b) Overloads the class's "new" and "delete" operators to use this
    object.  Each actual call to malloc will allocate <mult> instances
    of the class, which the allocator object will parcel out
    one-by-one.

(c)  Provides and additional, static method "memClear()" for the class.  

The objects returned by the overloaded "new" are always double- and
void*-aligned. 

When you call the overloaded "delete", the memory for the object in
question in question will be reused by later calls to "new", but only
for the same kind of object.  If it becomes critical, I think it
should be possible to overcome this restriction and have several
similarly-sized classes share the same memory pool, but not with the
simple includes/macros described above.

The <class-name>::memClear() method truly frees all memory associated
with <class-name> objects.  If called with no arguments, or an argument of
TRUE, it also does a cursory check for obvious memory leaks.  If
called with an argument of FALSE, this check is omitted.  MemClear()
should be used with caution, since ALL pointers to <class-name>
objects will be invalid as soon as it returns.

